    <stitle>International&#174; MaxxForce&#8482; 7 Engine Service Manual - Power Cylinders - Installation - Connecting
        Rod and Piston Assembly
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="s14.4.2" svcproctype="install" graphiccount="7">
        <title>Connecting Rod and Piston Assembly</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Turn crankshaft so number 1 crank pin is at bottom of its stroke.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f3450014021" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd04/D0410.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="192px"/>
            <caption>Piston and piston ring lubrication</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Lightly coat piston and piston rings with clean engine oil.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f3450014022" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd06/D0613.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="192px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Cylinder wall lubrication</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Coat cylinder walls, crankshaft journals, and
                <hotlnk document="eges3451_299.xml" xrefid="s14.t3">piston ring compressor (cope) ZTSE4514</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s14.t3"/>
                with clean engine oil.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f3450014023" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd04/D0415.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="192px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Piston installed in piston ring compressor (cope) ZTSE4514</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Place piston in
                <hotlnk document="eges3451_299.xml" xrefid="s14.t3">piston ring compressor (cope) ZTSE4514</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s14.t3"/>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install bearing shells in connecting rod and cap. Coat bearing shell in connecting rod with
                clean engine oil.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f3450014024" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figM04/M04106.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="192px" box="no"/>
            <caption>CAM SIDE stamp on piston</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, CAM SIDE stamped on top of piston must face camshaft side of
                    crankcase.
                </para>
            </caution>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, do not damage piston cooling tube when installing connecting rod and
                    piston assembly. If tube is bent during piston assembly installation, replace tube.
                </para>
            </caution>
            <note>
                <para>Before installing piston and connecting rod assembly, make sure all piston cooling tubes are
                    installed.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Carefully put piston and piston cope combination and connecting rod assembly in cylinder
                bore.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f3450014025" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd04/D0411A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="192px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Installation of piston in cylinder bore</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Once piston and connecting rod assembly have been inserted in cylinder bore, use a handle
                (wood or plastic) of a hammer to tap piston into crankcase bore. Guide connecting rod in place on
                crankshaft.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, lightly lubricate bolt threads and mating surfaces of bolt flanges with
                    clean engine oil. Too much oil will cause hydrostatic lock and give incorrect torque reading.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Apply clean engine oil to bolt hole threads for connecting rod and bearing shell in cap
                before installing bolts.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f3450014026" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd04/D0412.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="192px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Connecting rod and cap</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Matching numbers or symbols</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, install connecting rods with correct caps in the correct direction. If a
                    rod cap is reversed, an offset will be seen at the mating surfaces. If a reverse assembly is
                    installed on the crankshaft, the connecting rod must be replaced. Also, check crank pin fillets for
                    damage that would require replacement of the crankshaft.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Assemble cap to connecting rod with matching identification code on same crankshaft journal
                from which it was removed. Be certain that longer leg of connecting rod and CAM SIDE stamp on piston
                crown are positioned towards camshaft.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f3450014027" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figM04/M04103.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="192px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Connecting rod cap</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting rod cap (8)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting rod bolt (16)</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, do not use air powered tools to install connecting rod bolts; this can
                    seize rod bolts.
                </para>
            </caution>
            <caution>
                <para>To prevent engine damage, do not rotate crankshaft until connecting rod is fully tightened, as
                    this may cause bearing shells to rotate in place.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install and tighten connecting rod bolts evenly to
                <hotlnk document="eges3451_298.xml" xrefid="s14.t2">initial and final torque values</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s14.t2"/>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Repeat installation procedure for remaining connecting rod and piston assemblies.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check connecting rod side clearance with feeler gauge. See procedure in
                <hotlnk document="eges3451_286.xml" xrefid="s14.2.ref1">removal section</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="s14.2.ref1"/>.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
